2. DESIGN REFERENCES — clean-room (recorded for provenance)
====================================================================

The following were used as DESIGN references only: the code was reimplemented
from public specifications (RFCs) or from the authors' own projects (bxp, axp
= Apache-2.0, relicensed by their copyright holder to MIT here; poc-wf-analytic
= same authors). No third-party source was copied. Listed with their upstream
license so any future line-level reuse is attributed correctly. A provenance
audit is pending before any public release.

  netaddr    — RFC 6724, RFC 5952 (specs); cross-checked vs Go net/addrselect
               (BSD-3-Clause, The Go Authors) + glibc getaddrinfo algorithm.
  http       — RFC 7230/9110 (HTTP/1.1); design ref: nghttp2 (MIT) for future
               HTTP/2; TLS via Zig std.crypto.tls.
  dns        — RFC 1035 (wire), RFC 8484 (DoH); design ref: miekg/dns
               (BSD-3-Clause) + c-ares.
  router     — design ref: go-chi/chi (MIT), julienschmidt/httprouter
               (BSD-3-Clause).
  ratelimit  — design ref: golang.org/x/time/rate (BSD-3-Clause, The Go
               Authors), nginx limit_req.
  abuseguard — design ref: nginx limit_conn (BSD-2-Clause), fail2ban
               (GPL-2.0 — documented behavior only, no code consulted or
               copied).
  throttle   — design ref: golang.org/x/sync/semaphore (BSD-3-Clause, The Go
               Authors; slot semantics only), Netflix concurrency-limits
               (Apache-2.0; design notes only), SEDA (Welsh et al., SOSP '01
               paper — bounded-queue load shedding).
  security-headers — design ref: helmet.js (MIT; defaults vocabulary + the
               `csp_helmet_default` constant reproducing helmet's default
               policy VALUE as configuration data, no source copied), OWASP
               Secure Headers Project; header semantics from RFC 6797 (HSTS),
               CSP Level 3, Fetch/HTML specs (COOP/CORP/COEP), RFC 9110.
  cors       — design ref: rs/cors (Go, MIT; preflight interception + the
               origin/method/header gate semantics) and expressjs/cors (MIT;
               reflect-request-headers default); protocol semantics from the
               WHATWG Fetch standard (CORS protocol) and RFC 9110. No source
               copied.
  resilience — design ref: resilience4j (Apache-2.0; breaker state machine,
               composition order, retry semantics), Polly (BSD-3-Clause;
               consecutive-failure count breaker), failsafe-go (Apache-2.0;
               delay/jitter policy shapes), AWS Architecture Blog
               "Exponential Backoff And Jitter" (Brooker, 2015; jitter
               taxonomy). Behavior only, no source copied.
  openapi    — design ref: FastAPI (MIT; the generated-spec shape and
               defaults, e.g. the default "Successful Response" 200 and
               path-parameter objects), utoipa (MIT OR Apache-2.0;
               route-metadata→spec mapping); document format per the
               OpenAPI Specification 3.1.0 (Apache-2.0, OpenAPI
               Initiative). Behavior only, no source copied.

  netlink    — kernel UAPI headers (linux/netlink.h, linux/rtnetlink.h,
               linux/if_link.h, linux/if_addr.h, linux/neighbour.h,
               linux/if.h; GPL-2.0 WITH Linux-syscall-note — constants and
               struct layouts are the OS ABI) + RFC 3549 (spec); design ref:
               libmnl (LGPL-2.1; validation/framing behavior only, no source
               consulted), vishvananda/netlink (Go, Apache-2.0; typed-query
               shape only). Clean-room, no source copied.

  aaa-gate   — extracted from the authors' axp project (axp-central/src/
               rest.zig: admin-token gate, auditMutation, AuditThrottle;
               Apache-2.0, relicensed MIT by the copyright holder); design
               ref: envoy ext_authz (Apache-2.0) and oauth2-proxy (MIT) —
               bearer-gate behavior only, no source consulted or copied;
               bearer semantics per RFC 6750, auth framework per RFC 9110.

  acme       — RFC 8555 (ACME), RFC 7515 (JWS), RFC 7638 (JWK thumbprint),
               RFC 2986 (PKCS#10), RFC 5915 (EC private keys); design ref:
               golang.org/x/crypto/acme (BSD-3-Clause, The Go Authors;
               nonce-refill/badNonce-retry + POST-as-GET client semantics),
               certbot (Apache-2.0; flow shape only). Behavior only, no
               source copied.

  kv         — design ref: Bitcask (Basho; Apache-2.0 — the published
               log-structured model: append-only CRC'd record file +
               in-memory keydir + merge/compaction; paper/design only),
               LMDB (OpenLDAP Public License) and xitdb (MIT) — embedded
               single-writer semantics only; TigerBeetle (Apache-2.0) —
               the VOPR deterministic fault-injection *approach* (simulate
               storage faults at every I/O step, assert recovery), not its
               implementation. Clean-room: behavior/approach only, no
               source consulted or copied.

  blobmsg    — extracted from the authors' axp project (axp-core/src/
               ubus.zig; Apache-2.0, relicensed MIT by the copyright
               holder); design ref: OpenWRT libubox (blob.h/blobmsg.h; ISC)
               and OpenWRT ubus (ubusmsg.h/libubus-io.c; LGPL-2.1) — wire
               format only, clean-room, no source consulted for this
               extraction and no source copied; byte-parity verified against
               `ubus -S` output on real hardware.

See each module's README "Provenance" note for its specific seed and reference.
